ight:1px solid #AAAAAA;"></td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">Outlet</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">Observation</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;"></td></tr><tr><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">Q</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">&lt;font color=&quot;BLUE&quot;&gt;Action Plan &lt;/font&gt;</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;"></td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">Chilled food delivered at higher than 8&#176;C should be rejected to avoid using unsafe food|Temperature of pasteurized juice/milk carton bottles should be taken by placing a sanitized probe thermometer inside of them|Product should be returned to the supplier or placed in a designated area for returned items and clearly labeled as so|Staff should be trained to wash their hands before wearing new gloves to prevent contamination|Gloves must be worn whenever handling ready to eat food without utensils to avoid contamination|Temperature of cooked food should be measured at the core using a probe thermometer|Food should be reheated on a high heat source (not in bain-marie) to ensure that it rapidly reached 75&#176;C|The cut should be cleaned and sanitized; a colored/waterproof band aid should be used to cover the cut; gloves should be worn|A food grade sanitizer or the dishwasher can be used to sanitize kitchen utensils|No, different cutting boards should be used to prevent any risk of cross contamination|Raw wings should be stored at the bottom of the fridge; the rest can be stored together, since they are ready to eat food|Individuals that are at risk of food poisoning are: Elderly people, infant, immunosuppressed individuals and pregnant women|The temperature of food in Bain Marie should be 60&#176;C or above|The temperature of food in Bain Marie should be 63&#176;C or above|Food on Bain-Marie that has been kept within the danger zone for more than 2 hours must be discarded|Probe thermometer should be sanitized before, between and after use to prevent any risk of cross contamination|Fruits &amp; vegetables should be sanitized to prevent any risk of contamination - to decrease the level of bacteria to a safe level|The best way to sneeze is in the shoulder. If in the hands, they should be porperly washed afterwards|Food should be cooked/reheated to 75&#176;C to ensure that bacteria in it has been properly killed|Cooking temperature as per the American System is: Poultry: 74&#176;C, Meat: 68&#176;C, Fish: 63&#176;C for 15s - the British System: 75&#176;C|No, raw eggs cannot be used to prepare garlic paste, hollandaise sauce, etc. because of a risk of contamination|The incident should be reported to the manager/PIC; and the pest control company should be contacted|No since some bacteria do not affect the smell, taste and appearance of the food|Cold food can be kept at room temperature for 4 hours|Fill a cup with ice and water. Place theprobe in a way not to touch the borders of the cup. A variation of 0+/-1&#176;C is acceptable|The same batch of food can be reheated only once to avoid the use of unsafe food|The correct temperatures of fridges &amp; freezers are 0 to 5&#176;C and -18&#176;C respectively|Staff should be familiar with the temperature danger zone which ranges between 5 and 63&#176;C to be able to monitor processes|Staff should be familiar with the temperature danger zone which ranges between 5 and 60&#176;C to be able to monitor processes|&gt;&gt;|~MULTIPLE~~VisibleInDropdowns~</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">0</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">1</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px solid #AAAAAA;">0</td><td style="border-top:1px solid #AAAAAA;border-right:1px sol